<p>HUMAN RIGHTS COUNCIL 
Second session  
Agenda item 2 
</p>
<p><b>IMPLEMENTATION OF GENERAL ASSEMBLY RESOLUTION 60/251</b> 
<b>OF 15 MARCH 2006 ENTITLED &#8220;HUMAN RIGHTS COUNCIL&#8221; 
</b></p>
<p><b>Rights of the child:  draft President&#8217;s statement 
</b></p>
<p><i> The Human Rights Council</i>, 
</p>
<p> 1. <i>Reaffirms </i>the Convention on the Rights of the Child and the Optional Protocols 
thereto on the sale of children, child prostitution and child pornography, and on the involvement 
of children in armed conflict; 
</p>
<p> 2. <i>Recalls </i>resolution 2005/44 of 19 April 2005 of the Commission on Human 
Rights; 
</p>
<p> 3. <i>Stresses </i>that effective and enforced criminalization, educational programmes and 
awareness-raising activities are important in preventing and combating the sexual exploitation of 
children and in reducing the demand for services deriving from their sexual exploitation; 
</p>
<p> 4. <i>Reaffirms </i>the need to continue to address the question of the demand factor in the 
commercial sexual exploitation of children as well as aspects related to prevention and 
rehabilitation of child victims of sexual exploitation; 
</p>
<p>GE.06-14463  (E)    041006 </p>

 <p> 
</p>
<p> 5. <i>Also reaffirms </i>the need to continue to incorporate specific rights of the child 
concerns in relation to armed conflict into the Council&#8217;s discussions and resolutions, and into 
technical cooperation programmes, including increased awareness of the six grave child rights 
violations identified by the Secretary-General (S/2005/72, para. 68) and specified in the 
monitoring and reporting mechanism; 
</p>
<p> 6. <i>Emphasizes </i>that the United Nations human rights system plays an essential role in 
ensuring the protection of the rights of war-affected children on the ground, including in the 
prevention of child recruitment, the release of abducted children, their reintegration and 
rehabilitation, taking into account the rights and the specific needs and capacities of girls; 
</p>
<p> 7. <i>Welcomes </i>the participatory and consultative process in preparation of the 
Secretary-General&#8217;s study on violence against children (A/61/299) in close collaboration with 
Member States and United Nations bodies and organizations, other relevant intergovernmental 
and non-governmental organizations and, in particular, the unprecedented level and quality of 
participation by children;  
</p>
<p> 8. <i>Decides </i>to continue to consider the question of violence against children and to 
hold a substantive discussion on the Secretary-General&#8217;s study on violence against children 
during its fourth session. 
</p>
<p>----- </p>

